4.	Boards:

To keep up to date on developments in the domain and in the mud there are
several boards you should read.

To read boards, use of the mbs wizard soul is recommended. For an introduction
read 'mbh tutorial'.

The boards that are considered obligatory reading for every member of the
domain are (name, category, domain, as used by mbs):
- Admin, Adm, Genesis
- Info, Adm, Genesis
- News, Adm, Genesis
- Gd, Develop, Genesis
- Lpc, Develop, Genesis
- Mudlib, Develop, Genesis
- Tool, Develop, Genesis
- Gondor, Domain, Gondor

Recommended reading are:
- Discuss, Adm, Genesis
- Domain, Adm, Genesis
- Guild, Adm, Genesis
- Idea, Adm, Genesis
- Magic, Develop, Genesis
- Shire, Domain, Shire


Before you ask questions, you might want to make sure that they are
not answered on any of the boards mentioned above.

To learn how to use 'mbs', use the help info on 'mbs' supplied via the
command 
> mbh tutorial
> mbh mbs

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------


5.	Coding:

5.1	Examples and how to treat them:

Most domains in Genesis have grown over several years. In this time
old wizards left, new wizards joined, the mudlib and the gamedriver
were modified. 

Consequently, there is a lot of code out there that works, but is
completely unfit to be used as example if you want to write good
code. Therefore, before you use any code as example, please ask
someone knowledgeable if that code is fit to be used as example!


5.2	'inherit':

Proper use of 'inherit' saves CPU time, memory, and disk space.

Before you start coding in Gondor, you will have to have at least a
basic understanding of the concept of inheritance, and how it differs
from the precompiler directive '#include' (and from - horribile dictu
- paste and copy).

Use 'include' only if it is impossible to use 'inherit'.

Copy functions only if it is impossible to use 'include'.

Never copy a file of 100 lines just to modify 3 or 4 of them!

If you have files which differ only in a few lines (eg two
neighbouring rooms, a large and a small orc, ... ) you should consider
making one common file, and then configuring or inheriting this common
file.  

If you have more than 3 of those files, you should be prepared to
produce an excellent reason to explain why you didn't create a common
file. 

'I didn't know how.' will not be an acceptable reason.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

